sec.p:
For a thermogelling material to be used as a topical formulation, certain rheological properties are desirable both below and above the gelation temperature. In this section we discuss these rheological properties of our canonical thermogelling nanoemulsion (Fig. 6). At ambient temperature, flow behavior similar to Newtonian fluids was observed at shear rates lower than 1 s−1; that is, shear stress linearly increases against shear rate and corresponding viscosity is independent of shear rate (a plateau in the viscosity at low shear rates) (Fig. 6a). However, at higher shear rates, the material becomes shear-thinning with a power-law dependence on shear rate, η ~ \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
